{"id":"1207.3276","submitter":"Josh Cadney","authors":"Josh Cadney and Noah Linden","title":"Measurement entropy in Generalized Non-Signalling Theory cannot detect\n  bipartite non-locality","comments":"14 pages, includes minor corrections from v1","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 86, 052103 (2012)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.86.052103","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider entropy in Generalized Non-Signalling Theory (also known as box\nworld) where the most common definition of entropy is the measurement entropy.\nIn this setting, we completely characterize the set of allowed entropies for a\nbipartite state. We find that the only inequalities amongst these entropies are\nsubadditivity and non-negativity. What is surprising is that non-locality does\nnot play a role - in fact any bipartite entropy vector can be achieved by\nseparable states of the theory. This is in stark contrast to the case of the\nvon Neumann entropy in quantum theory, where only entangled states satisfy\nS(AB)<S(A).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Jul 2012 15:17:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 13 Nov 2012 12:01:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-11-14"}
